passages.text: Monthly Aggregates - July- 25: Business Lending Regains Momentum

Credit growth for Jul- 25 increased to \(7.2\%\) YoY (Chart 1), driven by accelerating momentum in business lending. Broad money growth decreased to \(6.4\%\) YoY (Chart 2). From a market share perspective, ANZ continues to cede lending share, down 9bp in the last 3 months, as we await the new CEO's strategy update on 13 October. CBA continues to reinforce its market- leading deposits franchise, up 8bp in household deposits and up 33bp in total deposits in the last 3- mo.

Total credit growth (non- financial): System credit growth was up \(+0.7\%\) MoM \((+0.6\%\) prior month) and \(7.2\%\) YoY, with increasing momentum in business lending, but a slowdown in personal lending.

Housing credit growth: up \(+0.5\%\) MoM \((+0.5\%\) prior month) and \(+6.0\%\) YoY, driven by \(+0.5\%\) MoM growth \((+5.7\%\) YoY) in OO loans and investor growth at \(+0.6\%\) MoM \((+6.6\%\) YoY).

Business credit growth (non- financial): up \(+1.4\%\) MoM \((+0.5\%\) prior month) and \(+10.0\%\) year over year. The re- acceleration in business lending supports our expectations that the market will remain competitive as banks continue to capitalise on these margin- accretive loans.

Personal loan growth: up \(+0.4\%\) MoM \((+0.8\%\) prior month) and \(3.6\%\) YoY. There was a minor slowing from the previous month, but growth remains strong. Jun- 25 recorded the highest YoY growth in personal lending we have seen since May- 08, at \(8.4\%\) .

Money supply: Broad money was up \(+0.5\%\) MoM \((+0.9\%\) prior month) and up \(+6.4\%\) YoY. Transaction deposits were up \(+1.6\%\) MoM (up \(+10.1\%\) YoY) and non- transaction deposits were up \(+1.2\%\) MoM \((+3.7\%\) YoY).

Market share trends for BOQ- remain concerning, with lending down - 6bp and deposits down- 3bp over the last 3 months. However, the mix of this decline does align with their strategic pivot towards business banking \((+2bp\) in the last 3 months). JDO continues to do well in business lending.

ANZ and CBA continued strong growth momentum in their personal lending book, with share up \(+77bp\) and \(+74bp\) respectively in the most recent 6- mo. Along with their declines in housing share, WBC has lost \(- 104bp\) in personal lending over the same period.
